350. ferat: subj. because in orat. obl. after edere.

351. trepidi oris. Genitive of description with T rachinius (sc. heros or rex). The line aptly marks the kindly solicitude of the monarch sor his guest.

352. This speech of the herdsman shows little of Ovid's undoubted dramatic power. It is too prolix and bombastic to befit a speaker of humble rank (and scant of breath, 347), and the descriptions which it contains, however elegant, are quite inappropriate at a time when ‘ delay is ruinous ⁹, 376.

353. medio orbe: poetical abl. of ‘place where’ without pre- position.

354. videret : ‘ subj. by assimilation ⁹ to that of the sentence on which it depends, ‘ cum . . . respiceret ’.

The meaning is that the distance already traversed, on which the Sun looks back, is as great as that which still lies before him, i.e. he has completed the half of his career. We are thus told three times (cf. medio orbe and altissimus in the previous line) that it was noon·day. See Introd. xvi.

359. templa: 8n.

subsunt, ‘lies hard by.' Some of the older commentators proposed to take the line as referring to the home of Nereus on the ocean floor, but had this been the poet’s meaning, he would have expressed it differently.
